caption: I miss this amazing food. Please come back
Absolutely the best Malaysian I have had outside of MY. Keeping the Malaysian coffee house vibe alive here in NYC. Hoping you guys can open again soon.
These guys are the best dive shop in SF. I had a great experience gearing up as well as taking their Nitrox class. Their Monteray outpost is also excellent
Delicious
When I depart this world, I'd like to be buried in a bed full of tea leaf salad.  Thank you.
i love home

malaysian food, mmm, so tasty. Visited on a Wednesday I think. Had a friend come into town and she asked me to take her here again. Prices are fair I would say. Ambience reminds me of San Diego's scene.
It was good enough.  Just didn't really see what all the fuss is about.  Its a great neighborhood joint.
quiet atmosphere

Will be ordering from here again soon! We got the Nasi lemak, Kaya toast, Pandan chicken and Chilled spicy sesame noodles. Everything was good! The noodles were our favorite. The consistency was perfect. Tried the Bek kopi and it tastes like burnt marshmallows (in a good way) hahahaha wasn’t expecting that favor but i instantly liked it.
I was nervous to come back to Burma Superstar.  I was completely blown away the first time, but I was also battling bronchitis.

This place is an experience not to be missed while in NY.    It is, by far, my favorite restaurant in the city.   Be sure to try the tea leaf salad, coconut curry soup, and the wonderful desserts.  I love everything about this place
You must try the Kopitiam. I had the pumpkin pork stew, it was delish and quite savory. Good service though not top notch. Get here early cause it fills up fast with lines out the door.
Definitely a new favorite.  Try the fried catfish curry. Call in advance though because it gets packed.
Kopitiam is a must; great service; the flat flour noodle is one of the most amazing noodles i have ever had. It's worth driving all the way there to try it.
Chicken Pandam is especially delicious, I wish I lived closer to get takeout all the time. I really appreciate how they geared up to help the community through the economic disaster of the pandemic.
Pandan chicken was great
Malaysian food and the setting here is excellent. Went there on a Saturday. The staff was very friendly and attentive.

My Singaporean friend let me order. Bad move. I screwed it up... twice. It didn't matter. Everything was amazing. I got the Pan Mee, my friend got the Nasi Lemak, and we shared my accidental Kaya Butter and French Toast order.  Due to NYC drama, we couldn't get a table. Instead, we went to the park and ate next to squirrels and vagrants. "Listen..." as my Singaporean friend would say––if this food can be consumed in a park that smells like NYC and still tastes amazing, it deserves 5 stars. I'm not from SE Asia, but Kopitiam is the closest thing to home for my friend, and I'm glad I was there to share it.

Best food in New York, NY - I'm obsessed - the tea leaf salad is incredible , this restaurant is well worth the wait, plus you can look around the area while you wait - it's a win win - super fast and good service too !
recommended
My fav spot for quality malaysian food. Definitely worth a return trip. Feeling here is similar to a cafe in San Jose I liked.

Wonderful! There was about an hour wait for a table, but we were able to get seated immediately at the communal table. This was a great way to see and smell many menu items before we ate. Everything was fragrant and delicious. The wait staff was very helpful with suggestions and served the soup and prepped the salad at the table.

Kopitiam is a great spot! I used to love sitting inside and drinking hot teh Tarik in the quiet afternoons. It would get packed on the weekend. Now, you can sit under roof of their outdoor tables or order take out! Their kaya toast is delicious and you can buy the jam to make at home! Support this gem; they do a lot to hire diverse individuals from the community and support the elderly in the community as well.
A preferred location for quality Malaysian food. Excellent spot to spend time alone or talk business. Definitely worth a return visit. The bill was reasonable I would say.

Totally worth the wait! This place is amazing. They are consistent, and the food is flavorful. I like the tea leave fermented salad and this beef curry dish that falls apart, the meat is really tender. If you're willing to try new food, this place is good!
Cheap and yummy food. The place accepts card and has some outdoor seating!

The best Burmese food in the city. Tastes pretty authentic to me. The wait is horrendous though. Best and most authentic dishes to order: fried tofu, mohinga, cau swe thok (noodle salad), nan gyi thok (coconut curry noodle salad).
I recommend the Tea Leaf Salad! It was an interesting blend of lettuce, nuts, herbs, and most importantly, the tea dressing had an exotic but tasty flavor to it.
The crisscross mushrooms!!!
My top place for quality Malaysian food. Definitely worth a return visit. The bill was decent.

BEST MALAYSIAN FOOD IN THE US!! 😍😭 I would give the chef 10 stars if I could. Spot on flavours, generous portions, reasonably priced... what more do you want?!  We got takeout delivered— food was soo hot and well packaged.  Please open a branch in Michigan or Chicago!!

Excellent Muah Chee. Generous portions and peanuts. Would have loved if the pieces were cut smaller (more surface area for peanuts). No big deal since they are so easy to cut.  Their curry puff has a decent filling- slightly runny with some spiciness, but their crust needs work. What they had was something from a fried sesame ball. Slight crunch with a sticky-chewiness to it.
The best Malaysian spot in all of NYC. Super authentic. Highly recommend the Nasi Lemak, spicy sesame noodles, pandan chicken, teh tarek
(Translated by Google) good service  (Original) 服务好

One of my favorite restaurants in the city! My favorite thing to do on a weekend is to go to Kopitiam, order all of my favorites, and sit at the window by myself. Definitely try the kaya toast and nasi lemak!
Malaysian food, mmm, so fresh. One of the best spots of its kind in the area. There was fast and courteous service. The place has an awesome atmosphere. Food and atmosphere reminds me of Kansas City.
Nice place for quality Malaysian food. The service was friendly and sociable.
Amazing food 👌
Delicious homey Malaysian food 💓 Owners are very involved in the community. Great outdoor dining setup as they make food care packages indoors! :)
Excellent

Went there the second time bc I don't know any other Malaysian place that were open for dining outside. I was unlucky and happen to sit next to an influencer and the dish + service was distinguishly different from theirs to mine. Wasn't a big fan of their price anyway.
Sadly was not a fan!  Have had better Malaysian food elsewhere.

You walk up a set of stairs (about 4-5 deep ones -not handicap friendly) to find this small, apparently clean, and busy coffee shop, that also serves food. We love Malaysian food, and yet their menu and dishes on various tables looked uninspiring, so we only got drinks from here. A chocolate malt and a ginger with brown sugar. While waiting, we got a cup of water from the pitcher they have out....it was sink water, and this made me wonder if there is a difference between bathroom sink water and kitchen sink water, but this was definitely unfiltered bathroom water.  Anyhow, we both wanted to return our drinks, they barely had any flavor to them. Mine tasted like water, and I didn't taste any ginger or brown sugar...so they redid it and unfortunately, it didn't taste any better. 2 small cups of badly flavored water named something else for $8+  The staff seemed ok.... The atmosphere was nice. Nothing stood out. Oh, but I did add a star because they use paper straws instead of plastic straws. I love that...is it worth coming back for...sadly, no.

Charming and YUMMY spot.  I had fun sampling the menu here a while back!  It was very tasty--the chicken wings were VERY good. Spicy. The pork roll was great, too.  I can't wait to try the Hainanese Chicken Rice and the Criss Cross Shrooms... they sound delicious!

I had the Hainanese chicken rice, the spicy stir-fried duck tongue, the Malaysian Style half boiled eggs, and the rose bandung. I've been holding out for the chicken rice for a while now. Everything was really good. Food was tasty and service was great!
Yummy Malaysian food.

Used to be one of my to go place. I went to day to get the nasi lemak , teh tarik and kaya jam. The teh tarik was not packaged properly and it end up leaking to the paper bag. As a result, the bag broke and the craked the kaya jam. When I got home, the "nasi" in the nasi lemak was very soggy and overcooked. I felt betrayed why do they still serve the nasi lemak knowing that the rice was overcooked.
The worse.Malaysian restaurant ever.been too it's overrated portions are.tiny and you need to order a lot just.to satisfy your hunger.never again!!!!
Amazing, affordable Malaysian food and coffee, perfect for your COVID-19 hangover!

This place always surprises me with delicious plates of food. I’ve gone here with my cousin and my mom. Everyone approves!!! The Horlick brings back many memories from my childhood. Bonus, the owners are super awesome and do a ton for the community!

Growing up in Southeast Asia, the “coffee shop” or kopitiam experience was essential for community, a family breakfast treat, and getting your favorite bites on the go. I’m always looking for dishes like what I had back at the noodle stalls of Brunei, and Kopitiam certainly comes close to the experience! I’ll definitely be returning for this wonderful feeling of Home.

Malaysian specialties in a somewhat crowded and slightly chaotic (during busy times) but nice room. My husband is Malaysian so I have been to Malaysia and had Malaysian food many times. We sampled a few different dishes here and generally pretty decent but I don’t think they quite hit the mark.  Second visit 03/05/20. Still busy around 8 pm. Out of several popular dishes again. Can I make a suggestion? Please order more of the ingredients for those popular dishes so that they are available. We enjoyed the food that we had.
Really big portion sizes!

Having spent my younger years in Malaysia, this place reminds me of my childhood.  The kaya butter toast is fluffy and delicious, and the kaya has such strong flavor. The nasi lemak is nicely salty, but the rice is missing the coconut flavor. The dressing on the side does add a nice spicy kick.
Cozy spot great food!

I used to love coming here more often. Spacious restaurant with lots of seating. Staff was friendly.  Roti: it was okay. Pretty big portion and the curry was pretty good.  Indian Mee Goreng: a bit greasy and small portion.  Prices are reasonable. Food wasn't as memorable as it was to me though.
Delicious food! I want to try everything on the menu
This place is good for authentic Chinese/Malaysian/Singapore food
Best Malaysian food in NYC. Believe it. .. Edit (2 years later): prices up, food quality down, place now swarmed with tourists. Nothing great lasts forever, I guess.
Really good food, and diverse. Good for a quick meal, the place is always full and there isn't time or space to hang out long. The staff is friendly.
you can not find so much tasty Malaysian food at another place in NYC. i will visit again

This dish was super spicy, and when I say spicy, take the words of a Mexican guy that is used to chile de árbol, habanero, etc. Not the easiest food to try, but if you are adventourous enough this is your place. I love it because of its authenticity... I think 😜
Fun, casual place. Great for takeout or delivery (order was ready very quickly). Definitely try the soups and the kuihs. And the sambal greens are amazing.

Food was authentic, with good sized portions. The flavor of the nasi lemak was delightful, with the ikan bilis being crispy and spicy enough to compliment the rice. The samabl was crisp and clean. Fishball soup had just enough flavor that one didn't need the soy and chilli. Definitely would visit again!
Such friendly service and delectable brunch delicacies!

Disappointing to say the least. I decided to try this place due to recommendations reading Time Out, Bon Apetit and now it’s also on Food Insider’s latest video.  This is my brutally honest review. I had the nasi lemak which had too many fried anchovies, peanuts and cucumbers to count. The sambal was barely enough nor was it tasteful. I also ordered the otak-otak as a side dish which was completely bland with a tinge of a weird sour taste. My barley drink was tasteless, nothing special nor worth buying. The dishes honestly lacked in soul, it didn’t have the flavours and spices of Malaysia.  To my fellow Malaysians, please do not waste your money by trying this so called kopitiam because it won’t reach the standards of our food culture back home. It is true the restaurant is often packed but I realised it was usually filled with Americans or foreigners (non-Malaysians) who seemed to either never tried Malaysian cuisine or have been there for business or pleasure once before and assumed it is at par to the standards of my home country.  Don’t waste your time unless you’re expecting disappointment and a decrease in your bank account that you will never get back.
Horrible service! I was seated but ignored for service for 30 minutes. I understand they were busy but it certainly doesn't give them the right to ignore me. I had to walk out eventually.

Decent Nasi Lemak, cool vibes but looks extremly unsanitary. Kopitiam should just change to sit down restaurant style. The staff looked crowded all just wandering around behind the counter plus they have to serve the food anyways.
Bland food, not a great deal of flavor ... many of the dishes had dried anchovies which isn't a bad thing, but was pretty bland ... all in all, it seemed pretty popular but we found it very flat ...
Good food good price
Went for the big breakfast and it was good! Great place to go and enjoy a relaxing Sunday breakfast and a pot of tea. Prompt staff and friendly, well priced so go and have a go.
Malay style tapas p lit Good white coffee I fux with it

This was our first time trying Malaysian food and this restaurant just took us by surprise. Everything that we tried was delicious and we tried lot of items from the menu . I can't wait to visit the restaurant again in the future

an all day casual Malaysian cafe in Chinatown that’s disrupting the culinary world, a worthy recognition as one of the 16 best restaurants in America. Yet on a beautiful Sunday afternoon, we stumbled in with no wait, spending about $20 on a filling breakfast for 2. The nasi lemak (a Malaysian dish consisting of coconut rice, cucumbers, a boiled egg, and a pile of chewy fried anchovies with soy-roasted peanuts) + chilled spicy sesame noodles + sticky rice with kaya jam among their other dishes are perfectly satisfying for any time of day.
Amazing Malaysian food with a good selection of food to chose from. I would love to come back here again for future NYC visits
Amazing flavors, good prices

This is a go to for me if I ever want Malaysian food! Though I don’t drink coffee, the white coffee seems to be a hit with all my friends. Obviously sweet but it’s made with condense milk powder which is pretty unique!  To hit the spot, get the classic Kaya Toast. My persona love was the Milo French Toast! It was a taste of childhood flavors! So good!  Things can get pricey since it’s not Asia, but there is value in uniqueness. I usually eat at the restaurant and then take away snacks that they have which rotates a lot!
Good service, excellent food and drink, and a cosy, quiet atmosphere. This place is wonderful for relaxing with friends.

Went on a Saturday afternoon and it was full to the brim. People eating noodles, dumplings, kopi and what not. It's a very nice cozy place that serves Malay fare and specially their coffee. Service is good and food n drinks are well worth it. Good clean bathrooms too. They serve coffee in cute Jade/ceramic tea cups with a plain cracker biscuit. Since it was busy the day I visited I took the kopi to go.
Amazing appetizer

Our meal was meh. Wanted to love it because I read good things about it but everything was a bit bland and served lukewarm. We barely touched the pork tea-infused soup because it was so boring and flavorless.
Amazing food, loved every single dish!

Awesome spot for a cheap dinner. True Malaysian flavors, some a bit more exotic than I’d prefer. Location is pretty tiny with a order at the counter payment system. Newly is what I ordered AND liked.  Malaysian Kaya Butter Toast  Belacan Wings  Criss Cross Shrooms  Beef Broth Pulled Noodles
Definitely a place for some good old Malaysian food!

Overall a decent place if youre craving Malaysian food. A little pricey though... Pan Mee was a little dissapointing- the noodles were very thick cut and the broth could use a little more flavor. Nasi Lemak was disappointing- the coconut rice was not fragant, anchovies were very chewy instead of crispy. Oh Chien was the better food item we ordered.  TLDR- go there if you’re craving Malaysian food but do not set your hopes too high.

The food was very affordable and delicious! I will say that the foods we had were very salty and a bit oily; particularly the duck tongue meal and the oh chien (oyster omelette). I really enjoy the format of not having a designated waiter/waitress and ordering and paying like when you're at a regular takeout place.  It's a casual place and a bit cramped but nothing out of the ordinary for a small restaurant in the area. All-in-all, a great experience with Malaysian food!

The criss cross shrooms with extra chilli is a spicy food lover's wet dream. Also tried the duck tongue and the anchovies over rice. All the dishes were extremely well thought through and the flavours were spot on. On top of all this the staff are v friendly and helpful. Highly recommend.

their signature dish: nasi lemak. Coconut rice, anchovies, peanut and sambal are all completely on point. Can’t help the Manhattan prices though. Pity about the drinks though; tasted watered down.  Really cute space with friendly staff.  Portions are smaller than the usual gargantuan American sizes; but order a few items to share and experience a wonderful variety of flavours.

Food was great, reminded me of my time in Singapore. Nasi Lemak lacked the fried egg and we were too early for the chicken rice, everything else was great. Recommend the Teh Tarek for sure to my fellow Indians who have not been initiated to Asian Tea.

The only good reviews this restaurant is getting is from people that have never try Malaysian food. If you look carefully in the comments, all the bad reviews come from Malaysians themselves as we know and understand the true flavors of our food. I am not trying to defame this restaurant but they do not represent Malaysian food well. I am only putting this review here for fellow Malaysians who would travel all the way from different states just to get Malaysian food. So fellow abroad Malaysians, don’t waste your money and time here as they are another few Malaysian restaurants elsewhere. I came here all the way from Oklahoma only to be so disappointed by the food.
Great food good taste
Feels like a real kopitiam I grew up with in Singapore. 10/10 would go again.

Incredibly friendly staff, incredibly delicious food.  Well worth a two train ride from Brooklyn.  Standout dishes include the mushroom entree and the hand pulled noodles.  Leave space for dessert and order all of them.

I’m obsessed with Kopitiam and am convinced that they have mastered the recipe for Lobak. I’ve never tasted it the way they make it.  All their dishes are amazing, make sure to try the Nasi Lemak and the Michael Jackson.  A perfect take on Malaysian street food, it definitely took my mom right back home to Malaysia.
Tried some of their snacks & desserts. & I was blown away. Tasted beyond amazing.

As a Malaysian I was HUGELY disappointed by the Nasi Lemak (The main Malaysian cuisine). As I was really craving Malaysian food, I had not eaten earlier and was expecting something mildly satisfying. I was not expecting much as I know it is difficult to produce an authentic version of the meal here. However, this one took it down multiple levels as their Nasi Lemak was so so wrong. The main thing about the Nasi Lemak is the Sambal (the red sauce). First of all, it tastes nothing like it at all. It does not even come close. It tasted more like sambal belacan (which is different from sambal nasi lemak) than anything else. Secondly, it was SOOOOO little. They served the sambal in a tiny cup (x2 smaller than the ketchup cup served in McD's) and when asked for extra, you had to pay for it. So kedekut (stingy), NONESENSE! Sambals are usually given in generous amounts if you ever come to Malaysia (or go to other Malaysian restaurants in the US). The meal was really disappointing (To say disappointing does not actually cut it for me). I also ordered the Soya drink but I dont want to get on that much. It was obvious they bought the Yeo's kotak(box) drink, poured half of it in and watered it down to save cost. I believe they wanted to cut costs all around but I dont think it should be at the expense of quality. If you want to try authentic (relatively closer) to Malaysian food, you should go to Rasa near Washington St Park instead. I  am not sponsored by them or anything, I am just a Malaysian who has been living in the US for abit and know the difference. Apa ni, so meh only. The place was clean and cosy though.

This place was quite good. Was right in line with what I was looking for to fill my belly after a long day of work. Good portions, home cooking, and good prices. Loved the noodle soup, and the chicken wrapped in banana leaves, and had a nice surprise with a new coffee drink that I’ve never had before, Malaysian White coffee with butter. It was more of a desert for me, since I don’t usually do sugar in my coffee, but a desert I would choose any day.

This place is so delicious and so cute! The front door has an old pink rotary phone next to it. Once you're inside, it's a small, cozy environment. You order at the front whatever you want, then pay, and then you sit down and wait for the food to come out. The food was amazing. The chicken is absolutely great and the desserts are to die for. I really love Malaysian food and this place did not disappoint.
Meh food, small portion and overpriced
Food was great Trying to be a more adventurous eater — this place helped me along the way and is proving that to be worth it! I will be coming back

I went after reading Bon Appetit review.  For me, it was just ok, nothing to write home about. Did a  takeout following their recommendation.  It just didn’t hold up but even the flavors were just meh. Been to Malaysia many times, this nothing worth noting. Over priced but friendly staff.

(Translated by Google) I went to dinner and didn't have a rendezvous, so I ate the starch and oysters  I was surprised that the oyster shell was chewed too much The other menus are also very satisfying for the price  (Original) 저녁에 가서 렌당은 없어서 르시나막하구 계란에 전분풀고 굴이들어간음식 먹었어요  굴껍질이 너무 많이씹혀서 놀랬어요 다른메뉴들도 가격대비 만족도가 높을것같아요

Neat little eatery with some uncommon menu items. Food here is tasty but generally not stellar. The lobak (tofu skin wrapped pork) was delicious, though the salted egg chicken wings felt severely lacking in actual salted egg. White coffee is worth trying here if you haven't had it before. Food was somewhat pricey for the portions provided, and there's usually a wait.
Good Malaysian/Singapore style Kopi but 4x the price

Informal, order at the counter, grab a number and your food is delivered. You also will bust your own table. Lucky, they have people wiping down the community tables. Very nice people working here.  Food: mixed from delicious to average-ish. Their noodle dishes are good, but the broth didn't lift my brow. The Tofu skinned sausage was a party. I would definitely order that again. The chicken bites on on bone were good - crispy, hot and flavorful. I was definitely underwhelmed with the wrapped rice. It just seemed weak in its flavor profile, subtle, likely too subtle. I wish my experience was better here. I would try it one more time.
Good asian (malaysian/singaporean) craving fixer.

Great food, great service, low key atmosphere in a nice little package. Kopitiam has brought the flavor in a great way. This is a great spot to come with several people just so that you can share the different dishes.
Good place with nice people and tasty food
The broth was really good. Definitely reminded me of the similar dish in Korea that my family loves.

I tried this place after seeing several bits about it on YouTube and I was not disappointed. You will need to love anchovies to eat here though. Service was quick and the flavours were delicious. The prices did not match was is shown on Google though, they increased their prices.
Everything was delicious,  but we particularly liked the eggplant.  Amazing.
Food is delicious!
Great neighborhood cafe — the Malaysian white coffee, kaya butter toast & half boiled egg dish are musts.

Didn’t quite live up to the hype. I got the pork belly noodle soup and it was kinda one dimensional and didn’t have as much pork as I would have expected. Prices are reasonable and I want to try the desserts if I go again
My favorite place in NYC.

This is an awesome place. The menu isn't that big, but all of the served dishes are kind of uncommon and won't be found on a lot of menus. The served dishes were just delicious. Can really recommend this place in case you want to try something different and affordable.
Great breakfast.
The food was delicious and the service is super good very nice place I’m gonna be back for sure
This place is an absolute gem. Great prices and very fast service, for takeout and eat-in. I suggest trying the Nasi Lemak.
Good service, food and drinks. There isn't a whole lot of seating so try and go during off hours.

This place has really good Malaysian food, and pleasant and helpful service, even though it's an order-at-the-counter setup. Their specials aren't all always available, but they're fantastic when they are.
Sesame noodles were very good. Tried a few other noodle dishes. Nothing was particularly impressive.

Cozy shop with details that remind me of Malaysia. The food was great and service was also fast. Nasi lemak was a favorite but it sucks that they don't have a version without peanuts for those with allergies. Also had the pan mee and beef rendang, both good. The drinks were also 10/10, can't wait to come back.
lovely spot for fresh tasty noodles, yummy greens, specialty coffee and tea drinks, sweets of all sorts, and a friendly atmosphere.

This place is an experience more than just a restaurant. The food, the desserts and the drinks are excellent! Prices are low and the service of the staff is great. This is a must try in Chinatown but just a heads up it's small and it gets crowded, on weekends there's a wait, but they also offer take out.

This was one of the best restaurant experiences I've ever had. Every dish was rich, whether that be a sweet decadence or a savory broth.  The staff was impeccably kind and generous. The place is lively while still being relaxed. If you have any inkling of interest in trying out a "hip new place with a unique cuisine" you will not be disappointed. I am eager to chat with Moonlynn and Kyo again. Going to order new things every time until I've tried everything.

Cute place. Unfortunately, they had run out of some dishes we wanted to try when we visited. We ended up getting a nasi lemak, the pork rolls, and the Pan Mee noodle soup. Out of these, I liked the pork rolls the most, even though it’s an appetizer, because it had the most flavor. Everything else was good, but kind of light fare, and we were doing dinner. If you’re looking for a full “bring me to the heat and humidity of Southeast Asia and stuff me with flavor and pungency,” this place won’t exactly do that. If you want to smear some Malaysian experience on a cracker or just have wisps of pandan fragrance drift through your dreams, then this place can help you out with that.
pandan chicken is the best!
This is such a nice place. I got the Nasi lemak. It was superb. Price point is great.

Not my usual experience with Malay food. Didn't know what to expect. The dishes were somewhat tasty however the system/service was disappointing. And the coffee i orderd  (iced) wasn't as smooth as coffee should be, very lumpy. Would I try it again, that would be a simple no thanks.
Pretty nice food. Kind service. Warm ambiance. Alternative and hipsters patrons. I’ll be back. Another effort in the gentrification wave.
Delicious French toast with bits of peanut and sesame

(Translated by Google) Delicious pan mee, coffee, cake, brains and fatty rice - though the sambal was yellowish.  (Original) Delicious pan mee, coffee, kueh, otak otak and nasi lemak - though the sambal was yellowish.

I love the casual cafe concept here - it’s a really easy place to just drop by. And boy do I on the regular to pick up nasi lemak. If I’ve got time, I also love the pan mee. It’s usually pretty busy around dinner, but I can usually find a spot for myself and maybe a friend.
First time here. Very friendly staff. Not too small.

Specifically dainty with its menu with my favorite Pan Mee soup noodle which is paired with an excellent homemade chili soy sauce--hits the comfort points on a cold day.  Only order this classic Pan Mee if you love little fried fishes.
Quick service and small plates at reasonable prices. $35 for 5 dishes for the two of us worked great for a weekday dinner. Friendly staff!

Had dinner the night Bon Appetit announced their 2019 Hot Ten with Kopitiam landing at #6. Abit of a wait but worth it. Currently it's cafeteria style where you order then find a table. So food came out fast which was great. I assume such operations will not be the case as it's popularity grows. My top picks were the pan mee and nasi lemak. The pan mee broth is reminiscence of a mother's home cooking with the hand-pulled noodles and the unami-rich anchovy broth. There certain items that are are weekend only but can't wait to go back to try the other items!!
Very close to authentic Singaporean food. Could be priced better, especially for kopi.
Quite an authentic Malaysian cafe. Great food and fantastic Nyonya desserts.

Quaint Malaysian cafe that has a warm and friendly vibe. I went by myself and I would not recommend it only because I wanted to try the whole menu. Definitely try the house special coffee (they have a light version if you don't want it so strong) -- I got mine iced. The staff is super friendly,  so don't hesitate to ask if you have questions!
Adorable out of the way place.the food was good and the iced coffee was great!  The prices were good to allow to try numerous dishes.
Everything we ordered was great! We got the Kaya Buttered Toast, Lobak, Pulut Panggang, Chilled Spicy Sesame Noodle, and the Pan Mee
music so loud. music so loud. bad loud music  Live Eels n Turtles Serve Meal
Must try Malaysian food. This was my first visit to a Malaysian restaurant and we could not have been more satisfied with the quality of food. I would highly recommend this place.

I ordered the Pan Mee noodles and pandan beverage...  The noodles were not fresh, the dough was very yellow and didn't rise making the the noodles very flat tasting. There was no bounce texture to the noodles at all. The soup was ok, fried anchovies were nice but that's it.  The pandan beverage had 2.5 pandan leaves in the package. That is extremely excessive knowing that pandan is a very strong flavor. When you keep the pandan leaves in the bag for too long there is a residual taste to it. Think about steeping Jasmine Green Tea for too long, that's the flavor and aftertaste. Not good.  Going to clean up my table, I noticed that others also didn't finish their food and they were just throwing away like me. Would love to know their thoughts on the quality of the meal as well.  Overall pretty disappointed, as a fellow Malaysian I had a lot of hopes in this place 😔

I came here by myself and had a very delicious meal. Although i would recommend going with a bigger group as there are many amazing sounding dishes on the menu that i wanted to try. It’s a cute place with amazingly nice staff. There is no alcohol but you have lots of tea and coffee options which is even better.

Worth a trip to Chinatown for brilliantly good malaysian food. The coffee is wonderful. Desert and savory special change regularly. Lines are very long during peak hours. Plan your visit on off-peak hours.
Everything is delicious here. Must try the curry puff, coffee with deserts and everything else on the menu. Come hungry and with a group so you can sample all items.
Excellent. Very good and the food is accessible to westerners. I didn't realize fried anchovy is the same as Korean fried anchovy!

I first visited Kopitiam when they were in the smaller location and served mostly drinks. I am SO happy that they reopened and expanded!! They kill it with great combinations of spice and textures. I’ve mostly come here for dinner, but breakfast is great too. The Kaya butter toast or the French toasts are great options if you like sweet things, but I’m all about the spicy/savory Chilled Spicy Sesame Noodles (with an egg!) or the Pan Mee. Both are super flavorful and filling. Also, don’t forget to try their drinks! The pulled coffee is rich and comforting, but I also like their teas and see tons of people enjoying their homemade soy milk.
Love the place! I love the Kopi Tarik, kaya toast, salted egg chicken wings! Makes me remember the days I lived in Singapore. Best times!
I absolutely loved the food. You can feel just as comfortable dining solo as in a group. The atmosphere was pleasant. Authentic and pretty damn good Malaysian food is but a stones throw away.
The food is prepared quick, and tastes great! Really fair prices too on their long list of menu items.

The food here might still be palatable to the general public, but compared to the average Malaysian food, it is highly underwhelming. Ordered their Nasi Lemak only to be disappointed by both the taste and portion of their sambal. The sambal tasted nothing like the sweet and spicy condiment that any Malaysian would expect, just blended onion, garlic, and chili. Besides that, the sambal that they provided didn't even fill up half the small ketchup paper cup that contained it, and I was told that it would cost an additional 90 cents to get more sambal! Since when are Malaysians known for being stingy? I tried to look for soy sauce to salvage what I could of that abomination, only to find that they don't even provide soy sauce at the table! Granted, this place is new, but that is no excuse for such an appalling misrepresentation of Malaysian food and culture. If you're looking for legitimate Malaysian food in the US, just save your money for somewhere else. However, if you're just looking for overpriced, mediocre food, by all means go ahead.

Given how much I paid for the food, I expected much more than what was served to me. The drinks were almost flavorless, the Sambal of Nasi Lemak was extremely little, and the flavors of Sambal sauteed water spinach did not blend well. As Malaysians, all the dishes my friends and I tried (Nasi Lemak, Kueh Chap, Hainanese chicken rice, Sambal sauteed water spinach) tasted very differently from what we had in Malaysia. If you are a Malaysian looking forward to get a taste of home at this restaurant in New York City, please prepare to be disappointed.  Tldr: Food was expensive and not delicious. It made me feel very sad!
Nice place....great food and service.
Comfy space, friendly people, good prices, great food. Highly recommended.
Hainanese chicken and rice was pretty, large but bland. Iced Teh tarik was light as well.

Came to check out Kopitiam on a Friday during lunch just because of the buzz it received as one of Eater's best new restaurants in the U.S. Everything on the menu will run you less than $20 and everything is AMAZING. The iced kopi -- which I've never had before -- was really yummy, slightly toastier in my opinion and less sweet than a Vietnamese iced coffee, which I absolutely loved. Perfect for a sweltering New York City day. The cold sesame noodles were just bursting with nutty, spicy flavor, and the noodles themselves were lucious and fat and amazing to chew through. The chicken wings were crispy and salty and perfect when paired with the salted egg yolk side. And the purple rice wrapped in pandan leaf with kaya jelly was a delight -- the kaya jelly had an awesome coconut flavor and was thick without being lumpy or tasting like corn starch.  I can't wait to come back to NYC and try out the kaya toast and all the amazing desserts on the menu, not to mention the nasi lamek and Hainan chicken rice!
Authentic Malaysian breakfast food, the nasi lamak and pandan chicken were as good as many cafes in KL.
Small space with fantastic dishes. Get multiple dishes and share! Came during a 90+ degree day and the chilled sesame noodles with a side of kaya toast was perfect!
Great little cafe for some unique food. Get the toast with jam!
Bets dbay ever
Authentic Asian food
Every thing I’ve try to order, they don’t have it. The service was too slow, my sister in law finish her meal and our plates didn’t came yet. Awfull service.
Great for coffee & savory, high protein breakfast--be warned it gets really crowded. Portions are small, you will want to sample multiple options. The Malaysian spin on French Toast is fantastic.

Very good spot to experience some authentic Malaysian street food. The highlight was the kaya pandan toast, which has a very unique flavored jam that is a must try! Just a tad on the expensive side for a full meal.

Ordered a Milo dinosaur, a teh tarik, chicken rice and Kaya toast. The chicken rice was a little cold and the chicken was very chewy. Not very impressive. The Kaya toast was very good as was the Milo dinosaur. You can buy some of their homemade Kaya jam from this place and that stuff is really good. Would visit again for the drinks and breakfast food.

I'm from Singapore and I thought the flavors of the dishes were pretty on point. It was a good place to satisfy my cravings for food from home.  The only complaint I have is with the value I'm getting from each dish for the price - there were not many pieces of oysters in the oyster omelet (orh jian) and too few pieces of pork in the kway chap (and no pig intestines??)

Speaking as a Malaysian, this restaurant is legit. If you have to get one thing from the restaurant, get the kaya (coconut jam) toast. It reminded me about the breakfast I had during my childhood. Will definitely come back again next time I'm in town.

Kopitiam's Malaysian fare is complemented well by its casual ambiance, charming (but not flashy) decor, and quick service - the focus is all on the food.  I'd certainly recommend the Hainanese chicken. The meat was literally falling off the bone and is some of the juiciest chicken I've ever had. The coffee is also brilliant for my fellow caffeine heads; don't be shy to try Kopitiam's cultural take on sweetness and flavor!  The other dishes my friends had also seemed great. The prawn noodles looked flavorful and the mushroom dish I tried a bite of (you'll know which one it is) was absolutely brilliant in presentation and taste.  All in all, I had a great time and an even better lunch here. Especially given its close proximity to the nearest subway line, I'll definitely be coming back!

Such great place! I have walked by this little Malaysian cafe a few times but never stopped until last weekend's Friday when I really needed to sit dow somewhere to relax a bit and let me tell you this place was just what I needed. The prices are very good, the food was tasty and the service was amazing, such a friendly and kind team. Bathrooms were very clean and the overall music and decoration of the place invited me to come back to read a book, work a bit on my computer or sit down with a good friend. The place is just great, Loved the casava and coconut milk cake 🥰.
We got takeout and in the condensed milk containers for the Milo French toast there were 3 hairs. That ruined my family’s and my appetite so we didn’t really want to eat the rest of the food.
So good. Felt like I was in a true kopitiam back in Malaysia. I cannot recommend this place enough! They know how to do Malaysian food right!
The smells and tastes of home. Loved every bite.

Love love love u kopitiam. So many delicious small plate dishes and lovely South East Asian desserts. Everything on the menu is fresh, delicious and hella authentic. I’m sooooo infatuated w pandan-everything so this place really does it for me. :)
The coffe tasted like bustelo with lots of sugar. The coconut rice and sardines was good.
Tasty.
They have fresh durian
Yesterday we came here. My family really enjoyed a lot we had great experience. Affordable price and good customer service.

It looks like they moved locations not so long ago so they have more food offerings and I thought their space was pretty cute. These noodles were exactly what the promised. Lip tingling spice with cooling slices of cucumber, eggs and a generous sprinkling of sesame seeds and a nice helping of rice noodles. I personally am a bit weak when it comes to burning spicy and it was much spicier than I expected although I could still enjoy the flavours, I found myself stealing bites of coconut rice from the husband to try to cool my mouth down. I definitely would like to return since I’m a fan of fast casual restaurants and there is so much more on the menu to explore and the chicken wings the husband got were delicious.

A cute, cozy, versatile concept tied to unique flavors/textures on a great location for a cheap price. No complaints here. You take a number and find a seat. Lots of natural light coming into the space makes this a great place to study. Cute and folksy pastel colored furnishings and exposed brick walls.  The food offerings here really are special and I am real eager to try more of them.  I do wish that the menu could be better organized. As someone unaccustomed to Malaysian cuisine, it was challenging to identify flavor profiles among the many items and their portion sizes just by the prices.  Will definitely return.
As a Malaysian their foods are hit and miss but I still enjoy it.

The food is fine, but it’s a hit and miss - for example pandan chicken/chicken wings are too dry, cold noodles undercooked etc. Getting the savory stuff is sort of a gamble. I prefer to go here for dessert and tea, but only at odd hours. Otherwise prime time it’s a bit of a mess with more than 15+ people. Overflowing dishes near the trash area (you put away your own dishes) and grungy because there’s no time to wipe down between customers. Food orders coming through when customers haven’t found seating etc. The service is very nice but it doesn’t help with their current set up.  It’s fine when it functions as a cafe but as a restaurant, it’s inefficient and chaotic which unfortunately seems to affect what’s most important- the consistency of the food. The pricing also doesn’t justify the quality.  I’ve been here a few times and but most likely won’t return.

Hands down the best Malaysian restaurant I've been to in Manhattan. I'm glad it's mostly underrated (thx to a bunch of people who aren't experienced with south east Asian food). The pan mee is amazing, among top 3 soups I've had in my NYC life. The broth is light, filled with umami from the mushroom and anchovies, but without being salty. Then, the hand torn noodle balances everything, with the right al dente texture and freshly made taste that complements the crunchiness of anchovies. Basically, if you go here, you should try the ban mee as your first entree here, along with a couple of sides (for example, the shrimp paste wings are amazing). Then perhaps come back and work your way through the menu.
I think I like their desserts better as both my friend and I found some of their savoury dishes so so. Get the teh tarik and the layer cake with pandan!

Great place to quickly sample Malaysian food. Menu is small but tasty. Parking is impossible but that's the  neighborhood. Good place to meet a friend or grab some take out. Glutinous rice stuffed with shrimp paste was better but still unspectacular. Much-lauded malted drink was just an average hot chocolate. Nothing wrong with this place, but don't believe the hype.

After visiting Singapore I have to say it’s been hard to find the same Kopi Coffee outside of Singapore. Kopitiam has been the closest so far.  Had the Pandan Chicken and Lobak snacks today. Both items came through quickly even though the place seemed packed. Very juicy. Only thing bad which I took a star off for, is lack of hot sauce availability.

Food was great, especially the tea pork noodles from the Winter menu. Was crowded during lunch on Sunday so be sure to come early to grab a seat. Nasi Lemak doesn’t have any meat in it, just anchovies, for those who are used to chicken in it like at other Malaysian restaurants in the nabe. Prices were a little high.

Kopitiam is a great place to taste some of the well known Malaysian dishes. Nasi Lemak was very tasty and it came with generous portion. Pan Mee was hand made noodle that took a while to get but the broth was very nourishing and worth the waiting time. Also try the various sweet offering made with sticky rice as the light coconut or pandan flavor is delightful.

Best Malay food in NYC.  The staff is so friendly and helpful if you are not sure what to order.  If you are looking for something specific in thier menu it is great to call ahead to make sure they have it that day.  Otak otak is belt l get very flavorful. The chicken wings are a must.

Had some drinks which were undeniably good. However, when it comes to the dessert/kuih; (otak-otak, talam and ondeh-ondeh) they were horrible. They taste nothing like real Malaysian dessert. Cashier was snobbish and bad experience overall.

This restaurant is almost 100% authentic. I have lived more than 4 years in Malaysia and I'm married to a Malaysian princess. We had Nasi Lemak, Pandan Chicken and Pan Mee. The Nasi Lemak was good even though the anchovies did not really taste that authentic but I must say the Nasi (rice) was very good. The Pandan Chicken was however a disappointment.  Instead of using chicken with bones that is how I always had it before minced chicken was used. I had one bite of it and felt directly that something was wrong with it. My wife tried it as well and agreed with me so we called the waiter to explain that we did not think this was the real thing and we wanted to send it back. Here I must say the restaurant was 100% authentic. Instead of accepting this and taking away the 6 dollars from the bill he said that "he can't take it away as we had already dug into it and that he would throw all of it away". He offered us a dessert or drink instead...disappointed from an American perspective but it really gave the place a Malaysian touch. The Pan Mee came in about 10 minutes later and was quite good and up to my liking even though the 1 dollar dish in Malaysia would beat this one. After the meal you are expected to clean your table and clean up. This felt like an insult as we already tipped up when paying the bill. If I go back I will make sure to save the tip until after eating so I can adjust it to what I think would be appropiate.
They have very limited options and the food is quite bland. All items that we tried from the menu were terrible. Don't eat here unless your life depends on it
One of my favorite new discoveries, especially for breakfast! Get everything, but don’t forget the milk toast and try the sesame almond drink. Perfect on a cold winter day.

Taste good but over priced.

I mostly chose this place because it was close to an internet cafe my little brother needed to go to, but I'm glad I did!  I ordered the Lobak, Pulut Panggang, Oh Chien, shrimp soup, Bandung, some sesame drink, and some type of coffee (this was my bro, so not sure which coffee it was).  The Lobak is very delicious.  Despite being fried, it wasn't oily at all.  Instead, it was tender on the inside, very juicy and a nice salty-meaty-sweet.  It actually reminds me a little of Chinese lionhead meatballs in terms of flavor...but definitely not as strong flavored and much less saucy.  The Pulut Panggang was more subtly flavored and a close second.  The rice and filling were aromatic and very nicely perfumed by the banana leaf.  Be sparing with the sauce/paste here...too much and it will overpower the rice and filling.  My main was the Oh Chien.  The egg was somehow fluffy and sticky at the same time.  I think it was the seafood sauce that did this...it was partially the texture of soft glutinous rice.  I enjoyed it, especially the pockets of tender oyster inside.  I can't speak to the shrimp soup (my brother's), but all in all, it was very enjoyable.  My suggestion for interested folks would ve to get there prior to noon.  We arrived at 11:30ish, and it was nice and fairly empty.  By the time we finished (12:20) it was packed.  So packed, we had to maneuver to get out.  5/5...and I will be returning in the future.  My little bro also enjoyed it (he says his coffee was really good), and he plans to bring his gf next time she's feeling homesick and wants Malaysian/Singaporean food.  Additional notes: Quick food prep, CC accepted, however they run out of certain menu items so come with backups in mind.  Also, the "snack" items are fairly large and filling ( we couldn't finish our mains), so plan accordingly.

An outstanding Malaysian restaurant with authentic food and superb service. Seating here is limited, and this place gets busy, but it's well worth the wait. MALAYSIA 🇲🇾 Eat the World NYC review: Over the summer, Kopitiam moved into a larger space with room for the kitchen to spread its wings. The menu has followed suit and they now offer much more, but all the favorite food and drinks are still available. The focus is small plates of snacks and noodle bowls that show off Peranakan cuisine, the rich mixing of Chinese and Malay culture that has happened in Malaysia for decades. Like a storage unit or a basement, it seems the extra space finds a way to get filled quickly, as more customers are coming and Kopitiam continues to burst at its seams during popular hours.

Their white coffee is cocaine.  Malaysian spots aren't plentiful in the neighborhood, so Kopitiam is a gem. Bonus points to them for rocking authentic dishes! More bonus points for the service. It was on the fleek.  And that coffee. The traditional penang white coffee ($5; credit accepted) is a potent pick-me-up in a deceptively sweet, deceptively soothing, package. And you can get it iced. Hungry? Get the nasi lemak, coconut rice with eggs, cucumber, anchovies, and a tangy homemade sambal sauce.  Thank goodness Kopitiam moved to a new location, it's now a legit date spot. With seating.
Cool, cheap, tasty. Great service.
